	abstract = {{OBJECTIVE}: To examine whether spironolactone could reduce the severity of obstructive sleep apnea ({OSA}) and lower blood pressure in patients with resistant hypertension. {METHODS}: This was a blank-controlled, single-center study. Patients with resistant hypertension and moderate-to-severe {OSA} (apnea-hypopnea index {\textgreater}15 events/h) were enrolled and randomly assigned to the therapy or control group. Patients in the therapy group were administered spironolactone 20 mg once daily (up to 40 mg once daily for 4 weeks, if required) in addition to original antihypertensive medication. Follow-up was 12 weeks. {RESULTS}: Thirty patients were enrolled (n = 15 per group). After 12 weeks of follow-up, apnea-hypopnea index (21.8 +/- 15.7 vs. 1.8 +/- 12.8, p {\textless} 0.05), hypopnea index (9.8 +/- 11.1 vs. -2.7 +/- 16.8, p {\textless} 0.05), oxygen desaturation index (20.8 +/- 15.0 vs. 0.3 +/- 16.1, p {\textless} 0.05), clinical blood pressure, ambulatory blood pressure, and plasma aldosterone level (9.8 +/- 6.3 vs. 2.9 +/- 6.7, p {\textless} 0.05) were reduced significantly in the therapy group compared with the control group. No side effects were reported. {CONCLUSIONS}: Spironolactone reduced the severity of {OSA} and reduced blood pressure in resistant hypertension patients with moderate-to-severe {OSA}. These findings may assist in the treatment of {OSA} in patients with resistant hypertension.},
