iabetes, 6.3 years; 42\% with macrovascular disease; 59\% had undergone metformin monotherapy) were treated and analyzed. The median duration of follow-up was 6.3 years. The primary outcome occurred in 356 of 3023 participants (11.8\%) in the linagliptin group and 362 of 3010 (12.0\%) in the glimepiride group ({HR}, 0.98 [95.47\% {CI}, 0.84-1.14]; P {\textless}.001 for noninferiority), meeting the noninferiority criterion but not superiority (P =.76). Adverse events occurred in 2822 participants (93.4\%) in the linagliptin group and 2856 (94.9\%) in the glimepiride group, with 15 participants (0.5\%) in the linagliptin group vs 16 (0.5\%) in the glimepiride group with adjudicated-confirmed acute pancreatitis. At least 1 episode of hypoglycemic adverse events occurred in 320 (10.6\%) participants in the linagliptin group and 1132 (37.7\%) in the glimepiride group ({HR}, 0.23 [95\% {CI}, 0.21-0.26]). Conclusions and Relevance: Among adults with relatively early type 2 diabetes and elevated cardiovascular risk, the use of linagliptin compared with glimepiride over a median 6.3 years resulted in a noninferior risk of a composite cardiovascular outcome. Trial Registration: {ClinicalTrials}.gov Identifier: {NCT}01243424.},
